This plot is noisy because of the (thankfully) much lower counts. Modify your code from above to produce a plot with a 7 day rolling average:

covid %>%
  filter(departement == 69) %>%
  mutate(deceased_new = deceased - lag(deceased, n = 1) )%>%
  mutate(deceased_new_7day = roll_meanl(deceased_new, n = 7) )%>%

Days of the Week: Reporting Bias?

Take the covid dataset, group by the date, take the sum (sm_sum) of the variable deceased across all the dÃ©partements for each day, and add a variable wday giving the day of the week for each row of the data:

covid %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(sm_sum(deceased)) %>%
  mutate(wday = wday(date, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE))

Starting with your code from the previous question, compute the change in the variable deceased_sum for each, and compute the average number of new deaths by the day of the week:

covid %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(sm_sum(deceased)) %>%
  mutate(wday = wday(date, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE)) %>%
  mutate(deaths = deceased_sum - lag(deceased_sum,n = 1)) %>%
  group_by(wday) %>%
  summarize(sm_mean(deaths))

More Plotting Practice

For a final plot, pick any dÃ©partement and produce an arrow plot that shows the change in hospitalisation numbers over time. Rather than showing every day, just show the weekly change from Monday to Monday. Color the lines according the direction of the change and try to include a good scale for the x-axis.

covid %>%
  filter(departement == 69) %>%
  mutate(wday = wday(date)) %>%
  filter(wday == 1) %>%
  arrange(date) %>%
  mutate(
    hospitalised_1week = lag(hospitalised, n = 1),
    h_delta = hospitalised - hospitalised_1week,
    color = if_else(h_delta > 0, "red", "green")
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(date, hospitalised_1week)) +
    geom_segment(
      aes(xend = date, yend = hospitalised, color = color),
      arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.02, "npc"))
    ) +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "month", date_labels = "%B") +
    scale_color_identity()

You can change (hopefully easily) the dÃ©partement number and quickly see the changes for another region as well.
